I"	<p><b>Key Notes from OU Writing Course</b></p>

<p><b>Plan</b></p>

<ul>
  <li>characters</li>
  <li>setting - senses: sounds, feel ( touch ), odour ( smell ), flavours ( taste), sight</li>
  <li>point of view</li>
  <li>the dramatic present</li>
  <li>backstory</li>
  <li>habitual behaviour</li>
  <li>some degree of mystery</li>
  <li>
    <p>where the narrative begins and ends</p>
  </li>
  <li>could develop a playlist that ‘describes’ a character.</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Brecht’s Structure</b></p>

<ul>
  <li>WHO?</li>
  <li>WHAT? - event, situation, focus</li>
  <li>WHERE? - something that readers will recognise</li>
  <li>WHEN? - make precise about the time</li>
  <li>HOW? - who is doing what to whom</li>
  <li>WHY? - everything is a detective story</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Senses</b></p>

<ul>
  <li>sounds</li>
  <li>feel ( touch )</li>
  <li>odour ( smell )</li>
  <li>flavours ( taste )</li>
  <li>sight</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Character</b></p>

<ul>
  <li>physical / biological</li>
  <li>psychological</li>
  <li>interpersonal / culture</li>
  <li>personal history</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Portraying</b></p>

<ul>
  <li>interpretation</li>
  <li>appearance</li>
  <li>action</li>
  <li>thought</li>
  <li>speech ( dialect, impediments )</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Backstory</b></p>

<ul>
  <li>giving character history</li>
  <li>predicting what may next</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Showing</b></p>

<ul>
  <li>through dialogue and action - expand a moment in time</li>
  <li>describing the scene, characters - speed up time</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Gabriel Roth</b></p>

<p>irritated - Anger - murderous
troubled - Fear - death
not secure - Doubt - paralysed
interested - Excitement - adrenaline rush
layed back - Calm/ Bored - cool</p>

<p><b>Sources of conflict</b></p>

<ul>
  <li>Conflict with Society.</li>
  <li>Conflict with Someone Else</li>
  <li>Conflict with Self.</li>
  <li>Conflict with Nature.</li>
</ul>

<p><a href="https://www.ian-irvine.com/for-writers/article-5-how-to-create-conflict/">Ways to create conflict</a></p>

<p><a href="https://www.scribendi.com/advice/types_of_conflict_in_literature.en.html">7 Types of Conflict in Literature</a> -  Person vs Person, Person vs Self, Person vs Fate ( Gods), Peson vs Nature, Person vs Society, Person vs the Unknown / Extraterrestrial, and Person vs Technology / Machinery</p>
